@DR Evil *Well, "Practitioner Evil", since your reply has no relevance to my post, I'm not certain why you even bothered.  I retract my respect. Goodbye.

@DR Evil *While you are clearly not a practitioner, you also clearly have more than a casual interest in this: either you are a patient, or someone who has been victimized by one of these people.  Out of respect for your above average knowledge, I will give this to you the same way I have argued this with fellow practitioners.  You may agree or disagree with my position - I do not deny that my position is somewhat controversial after DSM-IV.*


*Until DSM-IV, BPD was considered part of the Narcissim spectrum of disorders, and in my experience, this is correct.  **_Unquestionably_** correct.  There have been no detailed long term studies undertaken to review the various BPD and NPD positions of the academy, and this is really unfortunate, as it is an area of research that is desperately lacking.  What we have instead is a few poorly designed, short term "studies" (I use quotes because they are so poorly designed that they qualify more as "quick look" than a detailed examination which can command the respectful term "study"), all of which have come up with conflicting findings (and even conflicting theories in some cases).  That said, a touch of history is probably in order before I continue.*


*When I was first in training (1978), BPD wasn't even "a thing" yet - that didn't happen until 1980 (?) with DSM-III.  Honestly, by DSM-III standards, I had never even seen a "Borderline" patient until the middle 1980s, and what the term really meant was questionable itself up through the middle 1980s.  In a way, that is still true, and that is a natural consequence of the method chosen for the DSM's construction (I would be surprised if you don't know what I'm referring to, but if not, please feel free to ask).  The biggest differences between DSM-III and DSM-IV and later is that DSM-III and earlier were concerned more with how you arrived than at **_hwere_** you arrived, whereas DSM-IV and later appear to be concerned **_only_** with **_where_** you have arrived - which is how I believe that BPD was erroneously separated from the Narcissism spectrum.*


*I am retired from medicine (I was not in psychiatry - I finished half of my psych residency and chose to start over in internal medicine) now, and have been for many years, however, because of my early intent to specialize in psychiatry I spent most of my active life working with PhD and PhD Candidate level psychologists as their "medical oversight", along with a close friend who stayed in psychiatry.  My medicophychiatric opinions are based upon that experience base.*


*That said, we need to give a quick acknowledgement to todays curious victim phenomena.  Victimhood has become a form of social currency, and that phenomena has much in common with both classical narcissism and classical borderline disorder.  I would go a step further, and say that based upon my observations, there has been a tragic pattern of pronouncing people as "BPD sufferers", who have nothing more than moderate neuroses (a term which is itself mostly deprecated, unfortunately).  These "diagnoses" are not, by and large, being made by those qualified to do so (psychiatrists and doctoral level psychologists), but by a combination of masters and pre-masters level social workers who have [tragically] been given state sanction to apply diagnostic criteria.  What we have today is a twisted landscape where (1) a diagnostic label of BPD is seen as some kind of "trophy" by many, and (2) wholly unqualified people are attaching BPD diagnostic labels to people based upon needs that are not psychiatric or psychological in nature - for example, the label may be needed to open some financial door (insurance or state subsidy), or to open some edicational door ("special education").  This has warped the entirety of the DSM systematology post DSM-III.*


*I believe the initial beliefs about BPD were correct - it is a manifestation along the Narcissism spectrum.  This does not mean that having a BPD primary diagnosis either requires or rules out a secondary diagnosis of NPD, it means only that there is by definition a Narcissistic substrate to the diagnostic disorder(s).*
